  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Prohibit financial transactions designed to conceal illegal proceeds\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious activities\n- Establish reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose criminal penalties for money laundering offenses\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\n4. Potential Penalties:\n- Significant fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Imprisonment\n\n5. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering laws that complement federal regulations.\n\nThese statutes are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to disrupt financial crimes.",
